orks across much of Asia. Introduced to India in the eleventh century by dynasties based in eastern Afghanistan, this culture would become progressively indigenized in the time of the great Mughals (sixteenth, seventeenth, and eighteenth centuries). Eaton brilliantly elaborates the complex encounter between India's Sanskrit culture—an equally rich and transregional complex that continued to flourish and grow throughout this period—and Persian culture, which helped shape the Delhi Sultanate, the Mughal Empire, and a host of regional states. This long-term process of cultural interaction is profoundly reflected in the languages, literatures, cuisines, attires, religions, styles of rulership and warfare, science, art, music, and architecture—and more—of South Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mrz 2021) 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  aafghanistan.  aasia.  aasian history.  abritish india.  acentral asia.  acolonialism.  acosmopolitan.  adelhi sultanate.  adynasties.  ahinduism.  ahistory.  aimperialism.  aindia.  aindian history.  aindian ocean.  aindian subcontinent.  aindigenous culture.  aindigenous peoples.  ainvasion.  airan.  aislam.  amaritime.  amodernity.  amughal empire.  amughals.  anonfiction.  aorient.  apakistan.  apersia.  apersianate culture.  araj.  areligion.  asanskrit.  asilk road.  asouth asia.  asouth asian studies.  asoutheast asia.  aspirituality.  atrade routes.  aturks.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052097423440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520974234423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520974234.jpg  a978-3-11-066763-9  UC Press eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles